Definition 35 Let $\textup{\bf X}\xrightarrow{T}{\textup{\bf B}}^{op}$ be an affine theory. A localic affine $T$-institution consists of: 1. a category S (of abstract signatures), 2. a functor $\textup{\bf S}\xrightarrow{I}{\textup{\bf B}}^{op}$. A localic affine $T$-institution morphism $(\textup{\bf S}_{1},I_{1})\xrightarrow{(\Phi,\alpha)}(\textup{\bf S}_{2},I_{2})$ consists of: 1. a functor $\textup{\bf S}_{1}\xrightarrow{\Phi}\textup{\bf S}_{2}$, 2. a natural transformation $I_{1}\xrightarrow{\alpha}I_{2}\Phi$. $\textup{\bf LAfInst}(T)$ is the category of localic affine $T$-institutions and their morphisms.
Definition 26 An institution $\mathbb{I}$ consists of: 1. a category Sign of signatures with $\Sigma$ denoting an arbitrary object, 2. a functor $\textup{\bf Sign}\xrightarrow{Mod}{\textup{\bf Cat}}^{op}$ giving $\Sigma$-models and $\Sigma$-morphisms, 3. a functor $\textup{\bf Sign}\xrightarrow{Sen}\textup{\bf Set}$ giving $\Sigma$-sentences, 4. a satisfaction relation $\models_{\Sigma}\subseteq Ob(Mod\Sigma)\times Sen\Sigma$ for every $\Sigma\in Ob(\textup{\bf Sign})$ such that for every Sgn-morphism $\Sigma\xrightarrow{\phi}{\Sigma}^{\prime}$, the Satisfaction Condition ${m}^{\prime}\models_{{\Sigma}^{\prime}}Sen\phi(s)\text{ iff }Mod\phi({m}^{% \prime})\models_{\Sigma}s$ holds for every ${m}^{\prime}\in Ob(Mod{\Sigma}^{\prime})$ and every $s\in Sen\Sigma$. An institution is called elementary (Sernadas1994, , Definition 3.1), Sernadas1995 (also pre-institution (Salibra1993, , Definition 1)) provided that the category Cat (in the definition of the functor $Mod$) is replaced with the category Set.
Definition 8 Given a functor $\textup{\bf X}\xrightarrow{T}{\textup{\bf B}}^{op}$, $\textup{\bf Af\,Sys}(T)$ is the comma category $(T\downarrow 1_{{\textup{\bf B}}^{op}})$, which is concrete over the product category $\textup{\bf X}\times{\textup{\bf B}}^{op}$, whose objects ($T$-affine systems or $T$-systems) are triples $(X,\kappa,B)$, which are made with ${\textup{\bf B}}^{op}$-morphisms $TX\xrightarrow{\kappa}B$; and whose morphisms ($T$-affine morphisms or $T$-morphisms) $(X_{1},\kappa_{1},B_{1})\xrightarrow{(f,\varphi)}(X_{2},\kappa_{2},B_{2})$ are $\textup{\bf X}\times{\textup{\bf B}}^{op}$-morphisms $(X_{1},B_{1})\xrightarrow{(f,\varphi)}(X_{2},B_{2})$, which make the diagram $\xymatrix{TX_{1}\ar[d]_{\kappa_{1}}\ar[r]^{Tf}&TX_{2}\ar[d]^{\kappa_{2}}\\ B_{1}\ar[r]_{\varphi}&B_{2}}$ commute.
Definition 4 Given a functor $\textup{\bf X}\xrightarrow{T}{\textup{\bf B}}^{op}$, where B is a variety of algebras, $\textup{\bf Af\,Spc}(T)$ is the concrete category over X, whose objects ($T$-affine spaces or $T$-spaces) are pairs $(X,\tau)$, where $X$ is an X-object and $\tau$ is a B-subalgebra of $TX$; and whose morphisms ($T$-affine morphisms or $T$-morphisms) $(X_{1},\tau_{1})\xrightarrow{f}(X_{2},\tau_{2})$ are X-morphisms $X_{1}\xrightarrow{f}X_{2}$ with the property that ${(Tf)}^{op}(\alpha)\in\tau_{1}$ for every $\alpha\in\tau_{2}$.
Definition 32 Given an affine theory $T$, $\textup{\bf AfInst}(T)$ is the subcategory of AfInst consisting of affine institutions $(\textup{\bf S},T,I)$ (shortened to $(\textup{\bf S},I)$) and their respective morphisms $(\Phi,1_{T},\alpha)$ (shortened to $(\Phi,\alpha)$).
Definition 2 Let $\mathcal{M}$ (resp., $\mathcal{E}$) be the class of $\Omega$-homomorphisms with injective (resp., surjective) underlying maps. A variety of $\Omega$-algebras is a full subcategory of $\textup{\bf Alg}(\Omega)$, which is closed under the formation of products, $\mathcal{M}$-subobjects (subalgebras), and $\mathcal{E}$-quotients (homomorphic images). The objects (resp., morphisms) of a variety are called algebras (resp., homomorphisms).
Definition 40 A generalized affine institution consists of: 1. a category S (of abstract signatures), 2. a generalized affine theory $T$, 3. a functor $\textup{\bf S}\xrightarrow{I}\textup{\bf GAfSys}(T)$.
Definition 28 A topological institution consists of: 1. a category Sign (of signatures), 2. a functor $\textup{\bf Sign}\xrightarrow{\mathcal{T}}{\textup{\bf TopSys}}^{op}$.
Definition \thedfn. We call $T\subseteq P$ tight if $T\succ T\not\mathrel{\widehat{\mathsf{C}}}P\setminus T$.
Definition \thedfn. We call $\mathcal{T}(P)$ the tight groupoid of $S$.
Definition \thedfn. A topological space $X$ is (1) locally compact if each point has a neighbourhood base of compact sets. (2) coherent if $X$ is locally compact and $\mathcal{C}(X)$ is closed under $\cap$, i.e. $O,N\in\mathcal{C}(X)\quad\Rightarrow\quad O\cap N\in\mathcal{C}(X).$ (3) stably locally compact if $X$ is coherent and, for $O\in\mathcal{O}(X)$ and $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\mathcal{C}(X)$ $\bigcap\mathcal{C}\subseteq O\quad\Rightarrow\quad\exists\text{ finite }F% \subseteq\mathcal{C}\ (\bigcap F\subseteq O).$
Definition \thedfn. For any relation $\sqsubset$ on $\mathcal{P}(P)$, we define a centred version $\widehat{\sqsubset}$ by $Q\mathrel{\widehat{\sqsubset}}R\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad\exists\text{ finite% }F\subseteq Q\ (\widehat{F}\mathrel{\sqsubset}R).$
Definition \thedfn. We call $P\subseteq\mathcal{O}(X)$ a (concrete) pseudobasis of a space $X$ if $\displaystyle\text{Every $x\in X$ is contained in some $O\in P$}.$ $\displaystyle\text{The subsets in $P$ distinguish the points of $X$}.$ $\displaystyle\text{The neighborhoods in $P$ of any fixed $x\in X$ are $\Subset% $-round}.$ $\displaystyle\text{Every non-empty $O\in\mathcal{O}(X)$ contains some non-% empty $N\in P$}.$
Definition \thedfn. We call $(S,\prec)$ a pseudobasic inverse semigroup if $S$ is an ordered inverse semigroup with zero and $P=S\setminus\{0\}$ is an abstract pseudobasis.
Definition \thedfn. For any $Q\subseteq P$ we define $Q^{\prec}=\{p\in P:\exists q\in Q\ (q\prec p)\}.$ We extend $\prec$ to a binary relation on $\mathcal{P}(P)=\{Q:Q\subseteq P\}$ by defining $Q\prec R\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad Q\subseteq R^{\succ}\qquad\Leftrightarrow% \qquad\forall q\in Q\ \exists r\in R\ (q\prec r).$
Definition \thedfn. An ordered inverse semigroup is an inverse semigroup $S$ together with a transitive left auxiliary relation $\prec\ \subseteq\ \leq$ preserving products and inverses, i.e. $\displaystyle q\prec q^{\prime}\leq r$ $\displaystyle\Rightarrow\qquad q\prec r\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad q\leq r.$ $\displaystyle q\prec q^{\prime}\quad\text{and}\quad r\prec r^{\prime}$ $\displaystyle\Rightarrow\qquad qr\prec q^{\prime}r^{\prime}.$ $\displaystyle q\prec r$ $\displaystyle\Rightarrow\qquad q^{-1}\prec r^{-1}.$
Definition \thedfn. We define the disjoint relation $\perp$ on $\mathcal{P}(P)$ by $Q\perp R\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad Q^{\succ}\cap R^{\succ}=\emptyset.$ We also define $Q^{\perp}=\{p\in P:Q\perp p\}$ so that we always have $Q\perp Q^{\perp}$ and $Q^{\perp}=\bigcap_{q\in Q}q^{\perp}.$
Definition \thedfn. The coset groupoid of $S$ is the set of cosets of $S$ with operations $\displaystyle C$ $\displaystyle\mapsto C^{-1}\quad\text{and}$ $\displaystyle(C,D)$ $\displaystyle\mapsto(CD)^{\leq}\quad\text{iff}\quad(C^{-1}C)^{\leq}=(DD^{-1})^% {\leq}.$
Definition \thedfn. $(P,\prec)$ is an abstract pseudobasis if $P$ is round, $\prec$ is transitive and $p\prec q\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad p\mathrel{\mathsf{C}}q^{\succ}.$
Definition \thedfn. We call $R\subseteq P$ round if $R\succ R$, i.e. $\forall r\in R\ \exists q\in R\ (q\prec r).$
Definition \thedfn. We define the relations $\mathrel{\mathsf{D}}$ and $\mathrel{\mathsf{C}}$ on $\mathcal{P}(P)$ by $\displaystyle Q\mathrel{\mathsf{D}}R$ $\displaystyle\Leftrightarrow\qquad\forall q\prec Q\ \exists r\prec R\ (r\prec q).$ $\displaystyle Q\mathrel{\mathsf{C}}R$ $\displaystyle\Leftrightarrow\qquad\exists\text{ finite }F\ (Q\mathrel{\mathsf{% D}}F\prec R).$
Definition \thedfn. We define the formal meet $\widehat{Q}$ of any $Q\subseteq P$ by $\widehat{Q}=\bigcap_{q\in Q}q^{\succ}$ We call $Q\subseteq P$ centred if $\widehat{F}\neq\emptyset$, for all finite $F\subseteq Q$.
Definition \thedfn ([LMS13, §3.1]). We call $C\subseteq S$ a coset if $CC^{-1}C=C^{\leq}=C$.
Definition \thedfn. We call $U\subseteq P$ a Frink filter if $u\in U\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad\exists w\prec u\ (U\mathrel{\widehat{\prec}}% w).\hskip 50.0pt$
Definition \thedfn. We call $P\subseteq\mathcal{O}(X)$ a pseudosubbasis of a space $X$ if $\displaystyle\forall x,y\in X\ \exists O\in P\ (x\neq y\quad\Rightarrow\quad x% \notin O\ni y\ \ \text{or}\ \ y\notin O\ni x).$ $\displaystyle\forall\text{ finite }F\subseteq P\ \forall x\in\bigcap F\ % \exists\text{ finite }G\subseteq P\ (x\in\bigcap G\Subset\bigcap F).$
Definition \thedfn. We call a collection of bisections $\mathcal{B}\subseteq\mathcal{B}(G)$ an étale family if $\mathcal{B}$ covers $G$ and is closed under pointwise products and inverses, i.e. $G=\bigcup\mathcal{B}\quad\text{and}\quad(O,N\in\mathcal{B}\quad\Rightarrow% \quad ON\in\mathcal{B}\text{ and }O^{-1}\in\mathcal{B}).$ An étale (pseudo)(sub)basis is a (pseudo)(sub)basis that is also an étale family.
Definition \thedfn. The tight spectrum $\mathcal{T}(P)$ of $P$ is the set of non-empty tight subsets of $P$ with the topology given by the following basis, for finite $F,G\subseteq P$. $O_{F}^{G}=\{T\in\mathcal{T}(P):F\subseteq T\text{ and }G\mathrel{\mathsf{C}}P% \setminus T\}.$
Definition 4.1. Let $G$ be a group. A Hopf $G$-coalgebra $H$ is a family of algebras $H=\{(H_{x},m_{x},1_{x})\}_{x\in G}$ together with the family of algebra maps $\Delta_{x,y}\colon H_{xy}\rightarrow H_{x}\otimes H_{y}\ ,\qquad\varepsilon% \colon H_{1}\rightarrow{\Bbbk}$ and linear maps ${S_{x}\colon H_{x}\rightarrow H_{x^{-1}}}$ such that the following holds Coassociativity: for all $x,y,z\in G$: $(\Delta_{x,y}\otimes\mathrm{id}_{H_{z}})\circ\Delta_{xy,z}=(\mathrm{id}_{H_{x}% }\otimes\Delta_{y,z})\circ\Delta_{x,yz}$ Counitality: for all $x\in G$: $(\mathrm{id}_{H_{x}}\otimes\varepsilon)\circ\Delta_{x,1}=\mathrm{id}_{H_{x}}=(% \varepsilon\otimes\mathrm{id}_{H_{x}})\circ\Delta_{1,x}$ Antipode law: for all $x\in G$: $m_{x}\circ(S_{x^{-1}}\otimes\mathrm{id}_{H_{x}})\circ\Delta_{x^{-1},x}=1_{x}% \cdot\varepsilon=m_{x}\circ(\mathrm{id}_{H_{x}}\otimes S_{x^{-1}})\circ\Delta_% {x,x^{-1}}\ .$ We say that a Hopf $G$-coalgebra is of finite type if $H_{x}$ is finite dimensional for all $x\in G$.
Definition 4.11. Let $H$ be a Hopf $G$-coalgebra. A right $G$-integral of $H$ is a family of linear forms ${\boldsymbol{\mu}}=({\boldsymbol{\mu}}_{x})\in\prod_{x\in G}H_{x}^{*}$ such that $({\boldsymbol{\mu}}_{x}\otimes\mathrm{id}_{H_{y}})\circ\Delta_{x,y}(-)={% \boldsymbol{\mu}}_{xy}(-)1_{y}\ .$ A left $G$-integral is defined similarly.
Definition 3.1. Given a group $G$ and $\mathcal{C}$ a ${\Bbbk}$-linear monoidal category. $\mathcal{C}$ is then called a $G$-graded category, or simply a $G$-category, if there is a family of full subcategories $(\mathcal{C}_{x})_{x\in G}$ such that the following holds: (1) $\mathbb{1}\in\mathcal{C}_{1}$, (2) $\mathcal{C}_{x}\neq 0$ for all $x\in G$ and we have a decomposition $\mathcal{C}=\bigoplus_{x\in G}\mathcal{C}_{x}$, (3) for all $x,y\in G$, and $V_{x}\in\mathcal{C}_{x}$, $V_{y}\in\mathcal{C}_{y}$, if $\mathcal{C}(V_{x},V_{y})$ is non-zero then $x=y$, (4) $\mathcal{C}_{x}\otimes\mathcal{C}_{y}\subset\mathcal{C}_{xy}$.
Definition 4.14. We call a Hopf algebra $H_{1}$ unimodular if ${\boldsymbol{\alpha}}=\varepsilon$. A Hopf $G$-coalgebra is called unimodular if $H_{1}$ is so.
Definition 2.3. Let $\mathcal{M}$ be a right module category over $\mathcal{C}$ and $\Sigma$ a right $\mathcal{C}$-module endofunctor on $\mathcal{M}$. For $P\in\mathcal{M}$, $V\in\mathcal{C}$ and $f\colon P\odot V\rightarrow\Sigma(P\odot V)$, the ${\Bbbk}$-linear map $\displaystyle\operatorname{tr}^{\Sigma,r}_{V}(f)$ $\displaystyle:=(\mathrm{id}_{\Sigma P}\odot\operatorname{\widetilde{ev}}_{V})% \circ\bigl{(}(\sigma_{P,V}\circ f)\odot\mathrm{id}_{V^{*}}\bigr{)}\circ(% \mathrm{id}_{P}\odot\operatorname{coev}_{V})$ $\displaystyle=\;\put(15.0,-18.0){{\tiny$V$}}\;\raisebox{-0.4pt}{\scalebox{.16}% {\includegraphics[]{pics/part-tr-righmodt.pdf}}}\put(-27.0,1.0){{\footnotesize% $f$}}\put(-34.0,-25.0){{\tiny$P$}}\;\in\;\mathcal{M}(P,\Sigma P)$ is called right partial $\Sigma$-trace.
Definition 2.1. Given a ${\Bbbk}$-linear endocategory $(\mathcal{D},\Sigma)$, a trace map on it is a family of ${\Bbbk}$-linear maps $\{{\mathsf{t}}_{X}\colon\mathcal{D}(X,\Sigma X)\rightarrow{\Bbbk}\}_{X\in% \mathcal{D}}$ such that ${\mathsf{t}}_{X}(f\circ g)={\mathsf{t}}_{Y}\big{(}\Sigma(g)\circ f\big{)}$ for all morphisms $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle g}}{{\rightarrow}}Y$ and $Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\rightarrow}}\Sigma X$. We also say in this case that the family ${\mathsf{t}}$ is $\Sigma$-cyclic.
Definition 4.10. Let $H$ be a Hopf $G$-coalgebra, i.e. $H_{1}$ is a Hopf algebra. A left cointegral of $H$ is an element ${\boldsymbol{c}}\in H_{1}$, such that $a{\boldsymbol{c}}=\varepsilon(a){\boldsymbol{c}}\ ,\qquad a\in H_{1}\ .$ Right cointegrals are defined similarly using the right multiplication with $a\in H_{1}$.
Definition 3.2. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a $G$-category. A $\mathcal{C}$-module category $\mathcal{M}$ is called $G$-graded if there is a family of subcategories $(\mathcal{M}_{x})_{x\in G}$ such that (1) $\mathcal{M}_{x}\neq 0$ for all $x\in G$ and we have a decomposition $\mathcal{M}=\bigoplus_{x\in G}\mathcal{M}_{x}$, (2) for all $x,y\in G$, $\mathcal{M}_{x}\odot\mathcal{C}_{y}\subset\mathcal{M}_{xy}$.
Definition 2.4. A right module trace on a right $\mathcal{C}$-module endocategory $(\mathcal{M},\Sigma)$ is a family of ${\Bbbk}$-linear maps $\{{\mathsf{t}}_{P}\colon\mathcal{M}(P,\Sigma P)\rightarrow{\Bbbk}\}_{P\in% \mathcal{M}}$ subject to the following two conditions: $\Sigma$-cyclicity: ${\mathsf{t}}$ is a trace map on $(\mathcal{M},\Sigma)$ in the sense of Definition 2.1, Right partial trace property: for $P\in\mathcal{M}$, $V\in\mathcal{C}$ and $f\colon P\odot V\rightarrow\Sigma(P\odot V)$ ${\mathsf{t}}_{P\odot V}(f)={\mathsf{t}}_{P}\bigl{(}\operatorname{tr}^{\Sigma,r% }_{V}(f)\bigr{)}\ .$ Furthermore, we call a trace map ${\mathsf{t}}$ non-degenerate if the pairings $\mathcal{M}(P^{\prime},\Sigma P)\times\mathcal{M}(P,P^{\prime})\rightarrow{% \Bbbk}\quad,\quad(f,g)\mapsto{\mathsf{t}}_{P}(f\circ g)$ are non-degenerate for every $P,P^{\prime}\in\mathcal{M}$.
Definition 4.12. The element ${\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\in H_{1}^{*}$ is called the $H_{1}$-distinguished group-like element or the modulus of $H_{1}$. The $G$-group-like element $\boldsymbol{a}$ is called the $H$-distinguished $G$-group-like element or the comodulus of $H$.
Definition 4.5. A pivotal Hopf $G$-coalgebra is a pair $(H,{\boldsymbol{g}})$, where $H$ is a Hopf $G$-coalgebra and ${\boldsymbol{g}}$ a $G$-group-like element such that $S_{x^{-1}}S_{x}(a)={\boldsymbol{g}}_{x}\cdot a\cdot{\boldsymbol{g}}_{x}^{-1}$.
Definition 0.5. If $X$ is a quasiseparated scheme, it(s underlying topological space) has a basis of quasicompact open sets closed under intersections. Therefore, by [13, 3.5], the category $\mathcal{O}_{X}\text{\rm-Mod}$ is locally finitely presented and as such has a notion of purity: This is defined by exactness of the functors $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{O}_{X}\text{\rm-Mod}}(\mathcal{F},-)$, where $\mathcal{F}$ runs over all finitely presented objects (i.e. $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{O}_{X}\text{\rm-Mod}}(\mathcal{F},-)$ commutes with direct limits). We will call this notion categorical purity or c-purity for short, defining c-pure-injectivity etc. in a similar fashion as in Definition 0.2.
Definition 0.2. A short exact sequence in $0\to\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}\to\mathcal{C}\to 0$ in $\mathcal{O}_{X}\text{\rm-Mod}$ is geometrically pure (or g-pure for short) if it stays exact after applying the sheaf tensor product functor $-\otimes\mathcal{Y}$ for all $\mathcal{Y}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}\text{\rm-Mod}$; equivalently, [3, Proposition 3.2], if the sequence of $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$-modules $0\to\mathcal{A}_{x}\to\mathcal{B}_{x}\to\mathcal{C}_{x}\to 0$ is pure-exact for each $x\in X$. We define g-pure monomorphisms and g-pure epimorphisms in the obvious way. An $\mathcal{O}_{X}$-module $\mathcal{N}$ is g-pure-injective if the functor $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{O}_{X}\text{\rm-Mod}}(-,\mathcal{N})$ is exact on g-pure exact sequences of $\mathcal{O}_{X}$-modules.
Definition 4.7. Let $X$ be a concentrated scheme. We denote by $\mbc D_{X}$ the definable subcategory of $\operatorname{QCoh}(X)$ corresponding to the closed subset of $\mathrm{Zg}(\operatorname{QCoh}(X))$ from Theorem 4.6.
Definition 1.2 ([9, Part III]). A functor between definable categories is called definable if it commutes with products and direct limits.
Definition 0.3. Recall that $\operatorname{QCoh}(X)$ is a full subcategory of $\mathcal{O}_{X}\text{\rm-Mod}$. Following [3], we say that a short exact sequence of quasicoherent sheaves is g-pure if it is g-pure in the larger category $\mathcal{O}_{X}\text{\rm-Mod}$. By [3, Propositions 3.3 & 3.4], this notion of g-purity for quasicoherent sheaves is equivalent to purity after restricting either to all open affine subsets, or to a chosen open affine cover of $X$. We say that a quasicoherent sheaf $\mathcal{N}$ is g-pure-injective in $\operatorname{QCoh}(X)$ if the functor $\operatorname{Hom}_{\operatorname{QCoh}(X)}(-,\mathcal{N})$ is exact on g-pure exact sequences of quasicoherent sheaves.
Definition 0.1. A scheme is called quasiseparated if the intersection of any two quasicompact open sets is quasicompact. A scheme is concentrated if it is quasicompact and quasiseparated.
Definition 0.6. If $X$ is a concentrated scheme, then the category $\operatorname{QCoh}(X)$ is locally finitely presented by [4, Proposition 7]. Again, all the c-pure notions are defined for $\operatorname{QCoh}(X)$ in a natural way.
Definition 1.4. We call $\mathcal{C}$ a pre-cluster tilting subcategory of $\mathcal{B}$ if it satisfies the following conditions: • $\mathcal{C}$ is closed under direct sums and summands; • $\mathcal{C}$ is rigid, that is to say, $\mathbb{E}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{C})=0$; • $\mathcal{C}$ is strongly contravariantly finite and strongly covariantly finite. • $\mathcal{C}^{\bot_{1}}={{}^{\bot_{1}}}\mathcal{C}$. where $\mathcal{C}^{\bot_{1}}$ is the subcategory of objects $X\in\mathcal{B}$ satisfying $\mathbb{E}(\mathcal{C},X)=0$ and ${{}^{\bot_{1}}}\mathcal{C}$ is the subcategory of objects $X\in\mathcal{B}$ satisfying $\mathbb{E}(X,\mathcal{C})=0$. A subcategory $\mathcal{C}$ of $\mathcal{B}$ is called cluster tilting if $\mathcal{C}$ is a pre-cluster tilting and $\mathcal{C}=\mathcal{C}^{\bot_{1}}={{}^{\bot_{1}}}\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 1.3. A subcategory $\mathcal{B}^{\prime}$ of $\mathcal{B}$ is called contravariantly finite if any object in $\mathcal{B}$ admits a right $\mathcal{B}^{\prime}$-approximation. Moreover, it is called strongly contravariantly finite if any object in $\mathcal{B}$ admits a right $\mathcal{B}^{\prime}$-approximation which is also a deflation. Dually we can define strongly covariantly finite.
